description.plain:
Joey Bada$$, born Jo-Vaughn Virginie Scott (b. January 20, 1995) is an American rapper, actor, and record producer hailing from Brooklyn, New York. Becoming known for his rugged 90’s style, an invigorating outcome of his Brooklyn neighborhood and surroundings, Joey Bada$$ has been a staple in the hip-hop industry for maintaining an authentic, unique and versatile sound. Whereas other rappers may take fewer risks with formulaic projects, Joey never shies away from keeping his music raw and original.

He is a co-founder of the collective Pro Era, with whom he has released two mixtapes and toured the globe multiple times.

Joey gained recognition after he released his debut mixtape, 1999, on June 12, 2012 to critical acclaim and recognition, followed by Rejex in September, and Summer Knights on July 1, 2013.

His debut studio album, B4.DA.$$, released on January 20, 2015 (his 20th birthday) through Pro Era Records / Cinematic Music Group, sold an impressive 56,000 units its opening week making it the #1 rap and #1 independent album in the country. The project henceforth received acclaim from his critics as well as his fans and is the catalyst that has placed Joey among Hip-Hop’s elite, as the album has sold 148,000+ copies worldwide to date.

After his debut album, Joey has spent the better part of 2015 touring; playing overseas festivals; creating original music for soundtracks, such as Southpaw, as well as a national tour in the US, all while establishing the first annual Steez Day Festival in New York City on July 7th, 2015.

Joey’s sophomore album, ALL-AMERIKKKAN BADA$$, was released on April 7, 2017, despite being leaked about a week earlier (which was due in part to an early physical press of the album). The project includes features from heavy-hitters such as ScHoolBoy Q, J. Cole and Styles P, as well as known collaborators Kirk Knight, Nyck Caution, Chronixx and Meechy Darko.

In an interview with XXL, Joey Badass stated that he was influenced by Nas, Tupac Shakur, Black Thought, MF DOOM, J Dilla, Andre 3000, Jay-Z and The Notorious B.I.G. He has received heavy comparison to late rapper Big L. He has also been compared to Nas during his Illmatic era.

songs.full_title: Survival Tactics by Joey Bada$$ (Ft. Capital STEEZ)
songs.title: Survival Tactics

description.plain:
Joey BADA$$ uses the instrumental for “Survival Tactics” by Styles of Beyond Prod. Vin Skully.

Joey borrows a lot of different flows from older artists (to compliment the old boom bap style he themed his work around) across the whole mixtape. Definitely spittin' on that Biggie flow when he’s like “When niggas start equippin, throw the clip in, etc etc.”

It has been alleged that Cinematic Music Group, the label under which Joey released the 1999 album, credited Joey with this song in an effort to focus attention on him even though it was a collaborative work with Capital STEEZ.

According to an article by the Fader Magazine:

“Survival Tactics” had initially been credited to Joey Bada$$ and Capital Steez—Steez had found the beat, and the song was his idea—but it had been rebranded as “Joey Bada$$ featuring Capital Steez” by the time the video made by Cinematic’s multimedia partner, Creative Control, was released

songs.title: Paper Trail$

description.plain:
Produced by the legendary DJ Premier, “Paper Trail$” revolves around how money has changed Joey in a negative way. He refers to Wu-Tang’s “C.R.E.A.M.” throughout the track to illustrate the point.

Joey described this song as the proper intro to B4.DA.$$. in an interview with Power 106 Los Angeles:

To me, ‘Paper Trail$’ was like the real intro to my album. Basically, I wanted to establish the where mind state I was at. The setting is in a place before the money, where I’d come to a point of realization where, you know, all of this stuff is going on in the world, and my generation is so focused on clothes and everything, but we’re still trapped. We really locked into the system… The whole essence of it is that really everything about money ruined everything around us. And this song I took ‘before the money’ to the extreme, I really thought about, like, a time before money even existed. So it was like cash ruin everything around us.

songs.full_title: LAND OF THE FREE by Joey Bada$$
songs.title: LAND OF THE FREE

description.plain:
A political track that brings up mass incarceration, the bitter sweet contrast in American history for Afro-Americans, and Joey’s ambition to create change for the future.

The song was originally teased on January 16th for Martin Luther King day. ‘'Land of the Free’‘ was released on January 20th 2017—both Joey’s birthday and the day of Donald Trump’s inauguration—and is a single for Joey’s sophmore album AABA.

The artwork shows Joey in a ‘'Make Amerikkka Suck Again’‘ shirt with what seems to be an illustration of a Nazi eagle symbol, (Reichsadler). This can be interpreted as a criticism of Donald Trump’s 2016 campaign slogan ‘'Make America Great Again’'. Trump has been accused of ‘'dog whistling’' to the Alt-Right movement and other demographics who believe in white nationalism.

The backdrop is an illustration of inside the boats of the slave handle. This is the original image below:

songs.title: Hardknock

description.plain:
Historical Context: Joey BADA$$:

“The only concept that was really behind it was how the people refer to the ‘90s as the golden age of hip-hop. So '99 being the last year of that age, it was basically like a "last hope” type of thing you feel me? It also coincides with the whole Y2K epidemic that was happening during that time so I felt it was perfect synchronization during that time only in 2012."

Rated #3 on the RapGenius Top 100 Rap Songs of the Year list.

songs.title: Waves

description.plain:
Joey borrowed this instrumental from the Freddie Joachim track also titled “Waves.”

This is the second song released from Joey BadA$$’s first solo project, “1999,” recorded when he was 17 years old. His performance of the song on The Tonight Show with Jimmy Fallon netted the Brooklyn native significant publicity. It was released as a follow-up to his debut video, “Survival Tactics.” The second offering has BadA$$ spitkicking on family, tofu dreams, and having the illest waves in his hood over mellow swelling Rhodes tones and a funky bassline. If you rode out to “Survival Tactics,” cool out, relax and reminisce to this one. The project is being released by SOW the brainchild of Cinematic Music Group and Creative Control.tv
The beat was later sampled by J. Cole in his song “False Prophets”.
Follow Joey @joeybadass_. No days off… child labor. – via

This is the first official song from Joey Badass for sale on iTunes along with his single “Enter the Void.” Purchase those singles here.

songs.title: DEVASTATED

description.plain:
Joey first previewed “Devastated” at Coachella on April 16, 2016.  On May 24, 2016 during fellow Pro Nyck Caution’s first headlining show at Baby’s All Right, Joey revealed the song would release the following Friday. On May 26, 2016 “Devastated” released on Pro Era’s YouTube channel.

In the song Joey discusses his pre-fame problems, and how he was “devastated” because he had not blown up.  He shares a resilient message about turning his struggles into a strength.

Joey took to Facebook on June 22, 2016 to share a very personal story from his childhood:

It was a really devastating moment in my life. You know, watching my mom battle a serious struggle, for me as a young child wasn’t anything I ever liked to see and I’m sure no child likes to see that. I used to come home from school and see eviction notices on our door.“ He admits he decided then that he would somehow pay his mom back for everything she did for him.

Joey also tagged the moving spiel with #IUsedToFeelSoDEVASTATED, inviting his fans to head over to his official website and share their own #devastated story or story of greatness.

On January 10th 2018, Devastated became Joey’s first song to reach RIAA Platinum status.

songs.title: TEMPTATION

description.plain:
“TEMPTATION” finds Joey confronting racism and discrimination against African-Americans, a common theme explored throughout ALL-AMERIKKKAN BADA$$.

The intro and outro sample a recording of Zianna Oliphant, a nine-year-old girl from Charlotte, North Carolina. In the wake of the shooting death of Keith Lamont Scott by police, she made the speech to an audience at a council meeting.

Throughout the song, Joey asserts the same simple ideas as Zianna does in her speech – why does someone’s skin color and ethnicity have bearing on their innate worth?

Joey first previewed “TEMPTATION” as well as the album’s 5th track, “DEVASTATED” at Coachella April 16, 2016.

The production used on “TEMPTATION” takes a melodic, catchy sample from “Oh Honey”, a song by the soul music group during the late 1970s, Delegation.

description.plain:
This is the second straight song on 1999 that features Capital Steez.

After proceeding the fiery and extremely emotional track “Survival Tactics”, “Killuminati” does not by any means slow down the pace of the album, with Joey and STEEZ trading relentless flows while showing their love for wordplay and discussing their journey to put Pro Era on the map.

This song samples WhºK∆res by the producer Knxwledge.

songs.full_title: Love Is Only a Feeling by Joey Bada$$
songs.title: Love Is Only a Feeling

description.plain:
“Love Is Only a Feeling” serves as Joey’s first solo release following his 2017 sophomore studio album, ALL-AMERIKKKAN BADA$$, and was released as a single alongside “500 Benz.”

This track’s beat and chorus samples HOMESHAKE’s “Love is Only a Feeling,” and is produced by frequent-collaborator and veteran producer Statik Selektah.

“Love Is Only a Feeling” has Joey raving about a girl, detailing how she is making him feel and also expressing his gratitude for being with her. – This strongly contrasts with the song’s title and chorus, stating that love is only a feeling.

description.plain:
The seventh track on the 1999 mixtape uses the Datura Stramonium instrumental by MF Doom, which uses various samples. It’s worth noting that MF Doom used the melody in a skit marked as the sixth track on his album, MM.. Food.

Some may recognize this melody from the Fat Albert Halloween Special, and this chorus from Eminem’s Open Mic.

songs.title: Hazeus View

description.plain:
Track 6 on Joey Bada$$‘ highly anticipated debut album “B4.DA.$$”. Kirk Knight, fellow Pro Era MC and producer, comes through with a slow chill beat with a nice piano melody for this track.

On this song Joey contemplates his status as a rising star and his own spirituality, wondering if he’ll reach some greater understanding now that his music is starting to reach people and he’s becoming a sort of idol in his own right.

description.plain:
In a 2015 interview with Sway at South by Southwest, Joey spoke about the song’s meaning and how it was somewhat inspired by the Ryan Coogler film “Fruitvale Station”: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1DcZyEdSRBI

Joey premiered this song on The Tonight Show. He tackles social, political, and personal issues over a smooth instrumental.

In the last verse and chorus, Joey is seemingly speaking from his own perspective.

songs.full_title: ROCKABYE BABY by Joey Bada$$ (Ft. ScHoolboy Q)
songs.title: ROCKABYE BABY

description.plain:
“Rockabye Baby” is Joey Bada$$‘ and ScHoolboy Q’s reflection on their place in American society. Both rappers reflect on their drug dealing past and gang affiliations, and wage inequality for black people.

The track was released several hours before the official release on the 30th of March, to prevent it from getting leaked, and is the third single from Joey Bada$$‘ sophomore album, ALL-AMERIKKKAN BADA$$.

songs.full_title: LEGENDARY by Joey Bada$$ (Ft. J. Cole)
songs.title: LEGENDARY

description.plain:
“LEGENDARY” is the first collaboration from Joey and J. Cole as a result of 2016’s False Prophets remix. In this song, the two introduce ideas such as spirituality, contentment and inner peace. Additionally, they question the way they, as “legends,” live their life and influence those around them.

Though this is the pair’s first collaboration, Joey stated in a Beats 1 interview that J. Cole was one of his favorite rappers when he was around 15-16 years old (another being Kendrick Lamar). According to the interview, Cole sent his verse in the day before 4 Your Eyez Only was released.

One thing the listener may notice immediately is how different Cole’s voice sounds as compared to his recent material from 4 Your Eyez Only.

description.plain:
A more sombre and introspective track for Joey, “On & On,” a piano-heavy ballad, was the fifth single to support his debut studio album B4.DA.$$.

UK artist Maverick Sabre delivers background vocals and the refrain, while fellow Pro Era member Dyemond Lewis delivers a featured verse.

At a show in Miami, Joey told the crowd that this song reminded him of “Snakes” and “Righteous Minds” off of his 1999 tape.

songs.full_title: FOR MY PEOPLE by Joey Bada$$
songs.title: FOR MY PEOPLE

description.plain:
“FOR MY PEOPLE” details the social and political issues that people of color face day-to-day, such as police brutality, racism and other social ills. Joey also addresses his role as an artist and a voice in the fight for change against racism.

He continues to explore these themes throughout ALL-AMERIKKKAN BADA$$, with both the title and the content within a criticism of white America’s conduct.

songs.title: Daily Routine

description.plain:
For those interested, the OG sample is “The Highway Of My Life” by the Isley Brothers.

Part of the Songs from Scratch series which features rappers creating a song on the spot from scratch from a beat created from scratch. See where it all began:

http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kQG7oNIGzn4

At first glance, 17-year-old Joey Bada$$ is like any of the cool kids at school: confident, and reluctant to reveal his secrets. The moment the beat drops, though, it becomes clear he doesn’t belong. Not with the cool crowd, maybe not with anyone. On a Thursday after school, Joey and his Pro-Era crew assembled at Brooklyn’s Dunham Studios — backpacks filled with laptops, laptops filled with loops – to create a new song, from scratch. Within minutes, the beat Chuck Strangers made only the night before sent Joey searching the insides of his eyelids for bars beyond his years. “Daily Routine,” the first in yours truly and adidas originals “Songs From Scratch” series, was written right there on the couch in the control room and is available for free download below.

songs.title_with_featured: RING THE ALARM (Ft. Kirk Knight, Meechy Darko & Nyck Caution)

description.plain:
Taking a break on the album’s theme of black empowerment and inequality, Joey, Meech, NYCk and Kirk express their discontent with the current lack of skill in the rap game.

They combat this by showcasing their own dynamic lyricism, something that “Beast Coast” artists are known for. The “Beast Coast” is a movement started in New York by the Progressive Era (Joey, Nyck, Kirk, etc.), the Flatbush Zombies (Meechy Darko and his group), and The Underachievers.

songs.title: BABYLON

description.plain:
This is the 10th song off ALL-AMERIKKKAN BADA$$. This song has a reggae vibe to it as Jamaican Reggae artiste, Chronixx is featured.

The name of the song, Babylon, originates from the ancient Mesopotamian city, mainly used in terms of religion and the Holy Bible.

Rastas, who refer to Selassie as the Lion of the tribe of Judea, take offense to Babylon and also make reference to oppressors as Babylon. Oppressors of the Rastafari religion include Police officers, who since the creation of Rastafari in the 1930s preyed on members because of its rapid growth and the fear of an uprising and a mass rebellion. Rastas can often be heard describing the government as Babylon system, police officers, Babylon bwoy, Dutty Babylon etc.

 Joey saw it fit to include a Chronixx feature as Chronixx himself is a follower of Rastafari. Black people also face oppression from law officials in the U.S. as many black people have been racially targeted.

songs.title: AMERIKKKAN IDOL

description.plain:
The final track on ALL-AMERIKKKAN BADA$$ shows Joey outright denouncing the American government, tackling negative stereotypes and calling out the government’s plan to exterminate the black people of America.

This title is a play on the show, American Idol. The show ran from June 11, 2002 – April 7, 2016. Coincidently, the release date of this album shares the same date that American Idol aired its last show.

description.plain:
Enter The Void is psychadelic movies that shows a DMT trip, which is a drug believed to open the “third eye”, which also relates to Soulo’s “Pineal Gland” song.  A DMT trip is a hallucogenic experience that tends to be spiritual and leads one to answers through messages on their quest.



This is the first song from Joey Badass for sale on iTunes along with his single “Waves”. Purchase those singles here

Not long after the song was released, Joey revealed on Twitter that this song was actually a throwaway.

songs.full_title: Word Is Bond by Joey Bada$$
songs.title: Word Is Bond

description.plain:
First single off Joey’s album Summer Knights, due for release on June 12th.  The project was initially expected to be a mixtape or EP, but on May 28 (the date of this single’s release), the Brooklyn rapper tweeted Summer Knights would in fact be a full-length effort.

The track features a sample of the lyrics spoken by Tupac on the Big L song Deadly Combination, but the sample in the track is not Pac. The instrumental also contains a predominant sample of “Amour” by Kleeer

The track features a sample of the lyrics spoken by Tupac on the Big L song Deadly Combination, but the sample in the track is not Pac. The instrumental also contains a predominant sample of “Amour” by Kleeer

songs.title: Black Beetles

description.plain:
“Black Beetles” is the 13th track on B4.DA.$$. It is arguably the darkest song on the album and has Joey rapping about his self-esteem and how his experience being a rap star isn’t as great as he thought it would be.

The instrumental for “Black Beetles” was first previewed and introduced in the first B4.DA.$$ trailer.

http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7J9VcUKwSRw

Watch the video below to see Joey and Sway talk about the lyrics:

http://youtu.be/LP5D6Jlc_p8?t=10m19s

songs.title: O.C.B.

description.plain:
These are Joey’s “Only Child Blues.”

“O.C.B.” sees Joey reminiscing on his upbringing without birth-siblings and on his relationship with his parents. Conversations with his mother are sampled in the chorus and outro as well, further cementing the theme.

OCB, established  1918, Finistere, France, is also a popular brand of rolling papers throughout the world—as well as in Saint Lucia, where Joey’s mother is from.

songs.full_title: GOOD MORNING AMERIKKKA by Joey Bada$$
songs.title: GOOD MORNING AMERIKKKA

description.plain:
The opening track, “Good Morning AmeriKKKa” delves into the elements of this album: racism, freedom, politics, and happiness.

The song title is an innocent greeting to Joey’s views on “Amerikkka,” as noted by the spelling with “KKK” instead of the usual “C”. KKK is an abbreviation for Klu Klux Klan, a group that advocates white supremacy, white nationalism, anti-immigration and antisemitism. The 3 K’s is also likely a nod to Ice Cube’s debut solo album AmeriKKKa’s Most Wanted, and Capital STEEZ’s debut mixtape AmeriKKKan Koruption

songs.full_title: Y U DON'T LOVE ME? (MISS AMERIKKKA) by Joey Bada$$
songs.title: Y U DON’T LOVE ME? (MISS AMERIKKKA)
songs.title_with_featured: Y U DON'T LOVE ME? (MISS AMERIKKKA)

description.plain:
On this track, Joey confronts his identity and the identity of African-Americans within the context of America as a whole.

This is Joey’s version of an unrequited love song about America. He treats America as a female (Miss Amerikkka) who just doesn’t treat him right.

The “Miss Amerikkka” name stems from the personification of a country’s attitude towards one race and also from the lack of racial diversity in Miss America pageants.

Jamaican Reggae artist Chronixx is featured to sing the hook and the 2nd verse.

songs.title: The Light

description.plain:
“The Light” serves as the opener to 2020’s The Light Pack and introduces the listener to Joey Bada$$’s musical return after a three-year hiatus from solo releases.

In the song, Joey uses themes of light and darkness to elaborate on the experiences he’s gone through since his last solo release in April 2017—a topic that he announced in his May 2020 interview with COMPLEX. The rapper boasts his comeback and standing in the rap game while questioning his “inner light.”

The music video sees Joey paying homage to American singer and rapper, Bobby Brown, who produced one of Joey’s favorite albums—June 1988’s Don’t Be Cruel. In the video, Joey wears Brown’s red outfit from a 1989 party.

songs.title: Escape 120

description.plain:
Joey’s birthday is on January 20th, hence the title of the song. His debut album B4.DA.$$ is set to be released on his birthday, the day he becomes 20.

As Nas said on “Life’s a Bitch”:

I woke up early on my born day; I’m 20, it’s a blessing

Fun Fact: The producer Chuck Strangers stated this is his favorite beat he has ever made for Joey.

This song was originally featured on the New York Renaissance mixtape hosted by DJ Peter Rosenburg titled as Rosie At Rubber Tracks.

The title of the song is most likely a reference to the iconic Bonita Applebum by A Tribe Called Quest. Sorry Bonita is also spanish for Sorry Beautiful.

songs.full_title: SUPER PREDATOR by Joey Bada$$ (Ft. Styles P)
songs.title: SUPER PREDATOR

description.plain:
Joey titles the track after the infamous term “super-predator” coined by  John DiIulio. The song challenges the term, which has been used to demonize black youth as having “no respect for human life or future.” The term recently brought controversy during the 2016 presidential election where people have been critical of Hillary Clinton for using it to describe gangs of youth in 1996. Many believed she was referring to African Americans.

Video of her first using the term to demonize Black men:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ALXulk0T8cg

In addition to the song’s clear political implications, it can also be seen as a wink to Joey’s belief that he is next up to carry the torch as the King of NY hip-hop, extending on the previous track “Ring The Alarm” in which he says he was “born running with the baton.”

Aside from the song’s unmistakable 1990s NY rap sound and vibe, it makes several references, both direct and indirect to the lyrics of some of NY’s greatest MC’s including Biggie, Jay-Z, Method Man and Joey’s Pro Era co-founder Capital STEEZ. It also features Styles P, another NY hip hop legend.

In the final verse Joey rap’s about how his stock has been heating up for years now and he’s clearly “heir to the throne.”

songs.title: 500 Benz

description.plain:
As a follow-up to his acclaimed All Amerikkkan Bada$$, the politically infused album that was another huge step forward for the young MC, Joey brings us some new music produced by Statik Selektah.

For the latest we find Joey Bada$$ moving back to his creative, lyrically focused story-telling over smooth, bumping instrumentals that create an undeniable vibe. Joey reminisces driving through the city in his Benz stunting on the people, and the women that only noticed him when the money came. There’s no word yet whether he’s working on a full-length project to follow up but until then these new tracks will undoubtedly suffice.

description.plain:
This is a bonus track off of Joey BADA$$ debut album: B4.DA.$$.

Much of the song revolves around comparing dancing to life and romance. Throughout the song, Joey and Kiesza use dancing as an entendre for sex. It’s an upbeat and fun track where Joey strays from his typical political style to create a more pop-esque hit with a ligther message.

Joey has collaborated with Kiesza before on a song called “Bad Thing”.

songs.title: Survivors Guilt

description.plain: This song is a tribute to Capital STEEZ (The founding member of Pro Era and Joey’s main affiliate) and Junior B (Joey Bada$$’s older cousin and tour manager) who both passed away in 2012 and 2014 respectively. Capital STEEZ committed suicide by jumping off the roof of the Cinematic Music Group headquarters, while Junior B died after a car accident that left third degree burns on his body. This song was released on what would’ve been Capital STEEZ’s 29th birthday.

songs.title: Shine

description.plain:
Designed “for the body,” “Shine” is a smooth summer tune that focuses on Joey Bada$$’s new life. The Brooklyn rapper alludes to both his past and his future while detailing his struggle trying to find balance between success, fame, and hurry. The song is built around a sample of Roy Ayers Ubiquity’s 1976 song “Everybody Loves the Sunshine,” which gives a funk vibe to the song.

“Shine” is the only song off of Joey Bada$$’s 2020 The Light Pack EP that was teased before its release. It was first previewed on Joey’s March 2019 The Life I Live tour vlog, before being announced later in December with a second snippet. The teasing of the song escalated throughout the following weeks, peaking in late January 2020 on the occasion of Joey’s 25th birthday.

The song is built around a sample of Roy Ayers Ubiquity’s 1976 song “Everybody Loves the Sunshine,” which gives a funk vibe to the song.

“Shine” is the only song off of Joey Bada$$’s 2020 The Light Pack EP that was teased before its release. It was first previewed on Joey’s March 2019 The Life I Live tour vlog, before being announced later in December with a second snippet. The teasing of the song escalated throughout the following weeks, peaking in late January 2020 on the occasion of Joey’s 25th birthday.

description.plain:
The sixth track on Joey Bada$$‘ Summer Knights mixtape features Chuck Strangers on the hook, as well as Issa Gold from the Underachievers and Meechy Darko from the Flatbush Zombies.

Joey, Issa and Meechy stick around the theme of getting head and sticking to their roots, boasting about the Beast Coast’s spot in the industry.

Joey explained the Beast Coast movement and what it was supposed to bring to the industry in an interview on Sway in the morning

Like the whole Beast Coast movement, we about to put New York back on the map. We boutta change that and bring real lyricism back to the game, cause it’s much needed. We gon' call this shit Beast Coast and we gon' show, don’t ever sleep on the East again, it’s not allowed.

songs.title: Ready

description.plain:
Announced by Joey via his twitter, he already mentioned the title of his new Statik Selektah produced single “Ready.” Joey Bada$$ is “Back with a vengeance.”

https://twitter.com/joeyBADASS/status/700711607698120705

It’s also worth noting the Malcolm X quotation in the left side of the cover art, which reads, “So early in life I had learned that if you want something, you had better make some noise”. The quotation is very fitting for Bada$$ considering that he started his rap career while still a teenager in high school and caused a lot of buzz among the hip-hop community.

songs.title: DSL

description.plain:
DSL could have three meanings, one meaning “Da Special List,” potentially referring to some sort of artist list that he may be on.  Another is “The specialist, meaning some one who is particularly at an activity or subject, Joey in this case is a rap specialist. The third is an acronym for "Dick Sucking Lips” is a term used to describe women with a special lip structure particularly advantageous for blowjobs.



Khloe Kardashian is someone who is considered to have DSLs

songs.title: Show Me

description.plain:
Show me samples Men I Trust song Show me How, a daydreamy almost bittersweet love song. Emma Proulx, the accredited artist, refers to Emmanuelle Proulx, the vocalist for the Canadian band.

The style for a beat sample suits Joey Bada$$ particularly well. In a similar style to the original song, Joey raps about bittersweet troubles in love. We get the impression that his fame and success in rap have stained or even broken innocent love in the past, complicated by different personal desires and dreams.

songs.full_title: Let It Breathe by Joey Bada$$
songs.title: Let It Breathe

description.plain:
Released as a loosie to celebrate his 26th birthday, “Let It Breathe” is Joey’s first new material in 2021 and his first since his July 2020 single bundle The Light Pack.

He first teased this track on Twitter on January 19, 2021, saying that he would be releasing a song the next day to celebrate his birthday. Later that night, he played the full song on his Instagram Live while in the studio with Statik Selektah. Statik, the producer of the track, also acknowledged the song’s imminent release with multiple social media posts.

description.plain:
“Brand New 911” was first heard in the introduction of the music video of “Let It Breathe,” a loosie released in celebration of Joey’s 26th birthday. He confirmed this song would release on his Instagram story a week later on January 26, 2020, saying it would be released “within the next two weeks” in a two-pack with “Let It Breathe.”

However, the song was not officially released until its inclusion on his third studio album, 2000.

songs.title: THE REV3NGE

description.plain:
Embodying the maxim “success is the best revenge,” the song “THE REV3NGE” glorifies Joey’s return to the rap game, five years after ALL-AMERIKKKAN BADA$$. The vengeful single continues the rollout for Joey’s third studio album, which started with the release of the three-track bundle The Light Pack in July 2020.

The song was performed during several Joey concerts throughout 2021. On October 12th, the Brooklyn rapper reposted a video of his live performance, claiming that he would release the song if the post reached over 20,000 comments. The song was officially announced on January 9, 2022, along with a trailer previewing a cinematic music video for the song.

songs.title: Too Lit

description.plain:
After his Twitter tease yesterday (July 4th), Joey has followed through on his promise and delivered two new tracks today, including “Too Lit.” Produced by Statik Selektah, “Lit” is laid-back Joey at his finest: not too rushed, not too urgent, just confident and relaxed against an instrumental that feels just as cool as he sounds.

Joey Bada$$ talks about trying to navigate through a world that is moving as fast as his star is rising in the music world. He talks about “just trying to make his legacy last” and attempting to stay grounded through it all.

songs.title: Brooklyn’$ Own

description.plain:
“Brooklyn'$ Own” is dedicated to the legacy of Brooklyn in Hip hop and how Joey Bada$$ sticks to his roots and NYC borough.

This song was produced by Statik Selektah and released on March, 9, 2016.  March 9th is when famous Brooklyn rapper The Notorious B.I.G. died. As a Brooklyn rapper, Joey obviously look up to Biggie, he even made this song to commemorate the 19th anniversary of Biggies death.

songs.title: Norwegian Breakfast

description.plain:
Written while on a 2013 trip to Norway with Pro Era, seemingly over the Norwegian breakfast posted on his Instagram, we find Joey tackling social issues over a Bagir produced beat.

According to the producer the beat was sent on July 2nd and the song was written that day. Though it is not confirmed, it is believed that it was recorded that same day.

songs.title: Thugz Cry

description.plain:
This song was debuted with a live performance on Australian radio station Triple J’s “Like a Version” segment, during Joey’s tour of Australia in January 2018.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dPcclBGKAMw

It was cut from Joey’s sophomore studio album ALL-AMERIKKKAN BADA$$ because He couldn’t get the sample cleared. It uses both instrumental samples and lyrical interpolations of the classic song “When Doves Cry” by Prince and the Revolution.

Like the rest of AABA, “Thugz Cry” is about racism and the suffering in black communities, with Joey urging his peers to take control of their situation and find the strength to overcome adversity.

Joey is not the first rapper to sample the classic Prince song. Tupac also used it on one of his posthumous songs “When We Ride OnOur Enemies.”

songs.title: Funk Flex | Freestyle #003

description.plain:
On this freestyle, Joey Bada$$ comes through with some pure fire for Funkmaster Flex on Hot 97. His verses contain some off the top freestyle, and some writtens.

The last verse contains a subliminal diss towards Troy Ave, who was indicted for a shooting at a T.I concert two weeks before this freestyle dropped.

Joey had previous beef with Troy Ave via Twitter, and called him out on his song “Ready”:

My nigga Kirk just outsold Troy Ave

Troy Ave later responded with his diss track, “Badass,” where he called out Joey, as well as Capital STEEZ, who was a good friend of Joey and one of the founders of the Pro Era crew.

songs.title: The Blocks*

description.plain:
This song was first teased in a tweet made by Joey Bada$$ with the caption:

A lil something i wrote in light of all the fucked up shit goin on rn.. i need hip hop to have a hug

These “recent events” that Joey is alluding to are most likely the death of fellow rappers Juice WRLD and Pop Smoke, the latter of which is also from Brooklyn, NY just like Joey. Joey more specifically wrote this song in reaction to Pop Smoke’s death, which was by homicide.

This isn’t the first time Joey has felt the pain of a fellow rappers' loss. On December 24, 2012, close friend and frequent collaborator Capital STEEZ committed suicide by jumping off of a building. Since then, Joey has spent his career trying to pay homage to the late artist by helping get his debut album released and started an annual Steez Day Festival in his name.

It is unclear if this track will ever be released to the public or appear on any of Joey’s upcoming projects.

songs.title: Ground Zero

description.plain:
On “Ground Zero,” Brooklyn rapper Joey Bada$$ reflects on his own mortality in his triumphant return to hip hop. Bada$$ reflects on his own come-up in the rap game and juxtaposes his difficult upbringing to the lavish lifestyle he currently lives.

On July 24, 2019, Joey debuted the track during a concert in Seattle, Washington.

The official album promo on Hot 97 FM.

Notice the energy of Joey’s freestyle developing, going from the second verse off “Born Day (AquariUS)”, a track that was dropped the next day, to steadily more dramatic theological and social criticism-laden verses.

Radio host and Underground Hip-Hop representative Rosenberg throws in a very befitting (looped) Tragedy Khadafi beat, astoundingly close to the Pro Era repertoire and definitely something straight outta STEEZ’s or Statik’s library.

songs.full_title: Two Distant Strangers by Joey Bada$$
songs.title: Two Distant Strangers

description.plain:
“Two Distant Strangers”, appears as the closing track to the Oscar nominated Netflix short film by the same name, “Two Distant Strangers”.

Both the film and the song heavily touch on police brutality, systematic racism, and race politics in America. It is still unknown whether this song was solely created for the film. Or if it will appear on one of Joey Bada$$’s future upcoming albums.

songs.title: Facts

description.plain:
“Facts” is a currently unreleased song first teased at the joint Flatbush Zombies x Joey Bada$$ joint concert at the Red Rocks Park and Amphitheatre on April 13th, 2019.

It is expected to be released on Joey’s third studio album. The full song leaked on September 25, 2021.
